The authorities have known about illegal advertising for a quarter of a year, they cannot get rid of it.
We are completely helpless, they admit.
For a quarter of a year, the editorial staff of the online daily Aktuálně.cz has been following the story of a billboard in South Bohemia, which now attracts motorists to visit Lipno, where there is not only a tourist-interesting walk in the treetops, but also an Olympic park.
Highways officials know they&#39;re standing there in the dark, but they say they can&#39;t do anything about it.
There are hundreds, maybe thousands, of similar ads across the country.
According to officials, a flimsy law is to blame for making it impossible to remove illegal mobile billboards immediately.
They need a complex bureaucratic wheel first.
In the meantime, however, the company changes its name and the office is short on it.
Or just move the ad a few meters and the official process has to start all over again.
The Directorate of Roads and Highways admitted a quarter of a year ago: on the main road from České Budějovice to Lipno, there is a black advertising billboard on our property next to the state road.
Even three months were not enough for the officials to get rid of the unauthorized portable construction with a giant advertising poster.
As if no one minded that he was standing right next to the road, in a fifty-meter protective zone, where nothing is allowed to stand for safety reasons.
Road administrators say they simply cannot deal with the billboard because of the loopholed law.
Maybe load it up and take it away.
&quot;We can&#39;t just afford that,&quot; says Nina Ledvinová, spokeswoman for the Directorate of Roads and Highways, referring to the complex bureaucratic process that the removal of the billboard must precede by law.
The case of this particular billboard, the fate of which the online daily Aktuálně.cz began to follow in detail in the spring, is not unique and points to a general problem that the state and authorities cannot solve effectively and quickly.
In South Bohemia alone, the editors counted dozens of similar mobile advertisements placed against the rules right next to the road or close to it.
Other regions are in a similar situation.
&quot;We have difficulty forcing companies to remove the banners,&quot; confirms Jiří Klása, head of the transport department of the České Budějovice regional office, whose colleagues deal with similar stories.
According to Klása, the leaky law that binds officials is to blame.
First, they have to approach the owner of the billboard in a complicated way to remove the ad.
But company bosses are often unable to catch up, or they know a trick that Aktuálně.cz has already described in the past, when it began to take a more detailed interest in the issue: all you have to do is move the mobile advertising stand a few meters and the officials can throw the previous call to remove black advertising into the trash.
That&#39;s because the authority has to determine exactly where the illegal billboard stands.
&quot;If someone moves it and the coordinates suddenly don&#39;t agree, it is viewed as a new device and we have to contact the owner again,&quot; explains Jiří Klása.
The new law will not help.
The change could be brought about by a new law, which from September next year will ban billboards near highways and limit them on Class I roads as well.
Critics point out that the rules for cracking down on illegal and easily transferable ads will remain the same as before.
And the authorities will not be relieved.
In this way, companies can continue to earn tens to hundreds of millions of crowns a year by renting illegal spaces, and no one can touch them.
For example, the billboard inviting Lipno belongs to the Commerz Billboard company.
Officials know her well: the municipality of České Budějovice is currently conducting three administrative proceedings with her for billboards erected in black.
The company faces a fine of three hundred thousand in each proceeding.
These are multiple advertisements that were placed without permission in the protection zone of a Class I road.
The proceedings have not yet been completed, says Jaroslav Mráz, head of the transport department of the České Budějovice municipality.
The advertisement that Aktuálně.cz is interested in is not yet among these cases, but it will most likely be added to them soon.
According to Nina Ledvinová, spokeswoman for the ŘSD, the company did not respond to repeated written calls for removal, and the case will thus be brought to the table of regional and then most likely municipal officials.
Commerz Billboard is one of those suspicious companies that cannot be contacted.
It does not receive mail, and it canceled its official headquarters in Žižkov more than six years ago.
It is not even clear who is behind it.
In the past, the company&#39;s mail went to South Bohemian businessman Anton Fischer, who became famous for a sharp dispute with the head of the Czech representative office of the Hyundai brand.
However, Fischer, whose company Euro Billboard rents space from Comerz Billboard and offers it to advertisers, has denied any connection in the past.
At the same time, this spring, when the ŘSD became interested in advertising in Lipno at the initiative of Aktuálně.cz, Fischer had state officials send a letter for the mysterious Commerz Billboard company to his boarding house, where the company is said to be based.
Even from this address, however, no one has contacted the highway authorities to date.
A futile struggle.
Similar silence or non-transparent seat changes are not uncommon.
A few years ago, we gradually fined one company two million crowns.
But she changed her name and ID number and there was nothing to deal with.
The executor returned the case, the ads continued to stand, perhaps in other places.
We are quite powerless against similar companies and their business practices.
It&#39;s like fighting windmills, admits one of the officials on condition of anonymity.
No one has yet addressed the amendment of the law in this regard.
Aktuálně.cz spoke to several MPs who were interested in the problem.
But they haven&#39;t developed any activity yet.
On the contrary, there were deputies who wanted to extend the deadline for maintaining billboards on the main Czech roads.
The government rejected it.
Billboards are a very sensitive and somewhat schizophrenic topic not only for national, but also regional and municipal politicians.
On the one hand, they know about the social demand for their restriction, on the other hand, they themselves need them for advertising in election campaigns.
I don&#39;t hold the fairly well-established impression that if something doesn&#39;t work, the laws need to be changed.
Farmers will harvest less grain this year, but more canola and poppy, statisticians estimate.
According to the estimates of the Czech Statistical Office, this year&#39;s cereal harvest will be 6.7 percent lower than last year.
Nevertheless, this year&#39;s harvest exceeds the average for the last five and ten years.
On the other hand, the harvest of rapeseed (by 3.9 percent) and poppy (2.5 percent) will be higher.
This year&#39;s cereal harvest will be 6.7 percent lower than last year.
Farmers harvest 7.2 million tons of grain.
This follows from an estimate published by the Czech Statistical Office as of July 15.
The initial estimate a month ago was more pessimistic and predicted a tenth of a drop compared to last year.
But last year&#39;s cereal harvest was above average.
This year&#39;s harvest exceeds the average for the last five and ten years.
On the contrary, the rapeseed and poppy harvest will be higher this year.
Rapeseed growers will harvest 3.9 percent more than a year ago, when 1.256 million tons were harvested.
This year&#39;s poppy harvest could be 2.5 percent higher than last year&#39;s.
The expected drop in cereal production is caused by both a decrease in yield per hectare by 3.7 percent to 5.71 tons per hectare and a decrease in the area sown.
Farmers planted three percent fewer fields this year.
According to estimates, winter wheat, which is the most important cereal for the Czech Republic, will be harvested this year by 3.3 percent less.
At the same time, farmers sowed it in several fields.
However, the decline will be marked by a lower yield per hectare, which will drop to 6.04 tons.
Statisticians expect a drop of roughly one-fifth for spring barley, which is most often used for beer production.
The fall in yield is due to a 15.2 percent reduction in sown areas, but also a lower yield per hectare.
Winter barley, on the other hand, will be harvested by 6.3 percent more.
The rye harvest will also increase.
Statisticians estimate the rapeseed harvest at 1.305 million tons, which is more than last year.
The sown areas increased by 7.3 percent.
However, the yield per hectare will be 3.2 percent lower than last year.
This year&#39;s rapeseed crop will exceed the ten-year average by 13.3 percent, while the sown area is a third larger than ten years ago.
In the last four years, poppy fields have also been increasing.
This year, farmers sowed it on 35,543 hectares.
Compared to 2008, when poppy was grown on a record 70,000 hectares in the Czech Republic, the number of fields is half that.
Thanks to the expansion of the sowing areas, this year&#39;s poppy harvest will be richer.
It will rise against last year by 2.5 percent to 27,423 tons.
However, the yield per hectare will be 6.1 percent lower.
