Russia and Turkey: An Alliance of &quot;Irreconcilables&quot;?
It was a gesture that ended in crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce a formal end to an eight-month war of words and economic sanctions.
But as Vladimir Putin welcomed the Turkish counterpart in a lavish palace hall in St. Petersburg, I got the impression that Ankara wanted more than this reconciliation.
There was a handshake, yes.
But Putin wasn&#39;t smiling, and he barely exuded warmth, even by his measured standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, has repeatedly spoken of his &quot;dear friend&quot; Mr Putin - five times, according to one report.
I didn&#39;t count it.
He also promised that relations with Russia would not only return to their pre-crisis level, but would be even better.
The next day, one of the local newspapers wrote that Erdogan acted as if nothing bad had ever happened.
To me, his enthusiasm was telling the exact opposite.
But the lingering coolness that radiated from Putin showed that the Russian leader had not forgotten anything.
The real cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening speech: Turkey&#39;s downing of a Russian warplane on the Syrian border.
Moscow&#39;s reaction at the time was furious.
Putin dealt blows around him and accused Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The outrage was all the greater that it came from a supposed friend.
Rebuilding real trust will be difficult, perhaps impossible.
Russian public opinion has also changed since December.
For months, the state-controlled media has waged a massive all-out campaign against Ankara.
Suddenly it looked as if the Turks were to blame for everything.
More serious have been allegations from top government officials that Erdogan&#39;s own family has benefited from the illegal oil trade in parts of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He emphatically denied this.
But in St. Petersburg, the official message came that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting only happened because Putin got the apology he was asking for from President Erdogan.
Russia could declare such a victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of declaring a ceasefire are clear.
First and foremost, Erdogan was nearly ousted from power last month in a failed coup and therefore needs all his friends.
Repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey have also visibly shaken him.
There is also an economic motive.
Russian sanctions had a hard impact - especially the cancellation of charter flights that transport several million Russian tourists to the coast of Turkey every year.
This number has decreased by almost 90%.
As for Russia, tour operators and charter companies will certainly be relieved when flights are eventually resumed.
They make money from Mediterranean tourism at the end of the season.
Even this week, state television promised cheaper fruit and vegetables when imports of agricultural commodities from Turkey are allowed again.
&quot;Tourists there, tomatoes back here,&quot; as a report in the Vedemosti newspaper proclaimed.
But the visit had another political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West for what it sees as a weak response to the coup attempt.
In addition, the lingering animosity of protracted EU accession talks and the entry of Putin - who is eager to take advantage of the cooling to sever Turkey&#39;s ties with the West.
The Russian leader certainly scored bonus points when Ankara asked him for help from the elected authorities after the coup attempt.
