The new rules should apply to all persons without a Thai passport who decide to purchase a SIM from one of the local operators while in Thailand.
So not only for tourists, but also for people with long-term visas who, for example, work in Thailand or who got married there.
The Secretary General of the Office of National Broadcasting and Telecommunications Commission Takorn Tantasith informed that there will be no exceptions.
The plan to sell SIMs intended exclusively for foreigners was presented by the national telecommunications regulator at the beginning of August.
The authorities intend to introduce new measures that will enable tracking of their location within six months.
According to Tantasith, this is a means of preserving national security, which will allow solving criminal activities committed by foreigners.
The so-called tourist SIMs are also intended to help detect persons who exceed the permitted length of stay.
In addition to SIMs intended exclusively for Thais, special SIMs for foreigners should also appear at dealers within six months.
The difference will be the tracking function, which will be permanently switched on for cards intended for persons without a Thai passport.
It will not be possible to turn it off.
&quot;This feature is not available for SIMs for Thais, because we can always track them easily,&quot; added Tantasith.
It must be added that prepaid cards are not anonymous in Thailand like in the Czech Republic.
The seller requires proof of identity.
On the other hand, for several years one of the operators gave out free starter SIMs to tourists at airports.
They were thus completely anonymous.
The introduction of the same measure as Thailand is also being considered by ten telecommunication regulators from other Asian countries including, for example, Malaysia and Singapore.
Even in them, SIM registration is currently mandatory, however legal use of the tracking system is not possible.
However, the planned measure does not mean that foreigners are obliged to purchase a local operator&#39;s SIM when entering the country.
Of course, they can use roaming services with their own home SIM, in which case the Thai authorities will be short on them.
After the country&#39;s operators have crossed the border, i.e. after the SIM has logged in to their network, they only know the relevant network information.
So they know the phone number but not the owner information.
However, the difference in roaming prices compared to the rates of local operators is so great that even most tourists start looking for local SIM cards during their stay in Thailand.
The efforts of the authorities to supervise the movement of foreigners were immediately criticized by foreigners living in Thailand legally.
Tantasith calms down the situation and compares the upcoming system in relation to privacy protection to the obligation to provide a residential address in immigration documents.
In addition, the police will need a court order if they need to track a specific person.
Any misuse of the system will result in an unspecified penalty.
&quot;If a service provider tracks a SIM&#39;s location without a court order, they will be charged with a crime,&quot; Tantasith added.
The system should also maximize the use of prepaid cards.
While currently a specific number is recycled only after a 90-day period has passed, after which the given SIM has not logged in to the network, in the case of leaving Thailand, the number could be renewed after only fifteen days.
A luxury apartment in a new building in Vinohrady has a swimming pool and a hot tub on the terrace.
Why did you choose an apartment in a new building?
We were looking for a carefree apartment, where most of the care of the property is taken care of by the manager.
The condition was sufficient parking spaces and an elevator in the building, which basically disqualified the older building.
Not to mention problematic acoustics in old houses, problems with floor swaying, high energy requirements and the like.
A condition was also large terraces, which the old development is unable to offer.
Other interesting visits can be found in the magazine Moderní byt.
The entire interior was designed for you by architect Lenka Langerová with her colleague Kamila Poláková from the Artiga studio.
Why did you reach out to them?
Would you recommend working with an expert to anyone?
We would recommend cooperation with an architect to anyone who is designing an apartment from the beginning, as it is a very complex technical process.
The second level is the interior design itself: designers have a significantly better idea of the range of possible materials and are able to coordinate the interior appropriately based on the client&#39;s wishes.
We already collaborated with the architect Lenka Langerová on our mountain apartment, based on the personal recommendation of another client, and given that everything worked well, it was a clear choice for us when renovating our new apartment in Vinohrady.
What were your practical and aesthetic requirements?
We wanted a generous social and living space with adequate facilities for a family of four, designed as a modern but not cold interior.
The priority was to connect the apartment with the terraces and implement intelligent household control.
And, of course, the quality of execution had to be controlled.
Did you leave everything to the experts, or did you intervene in the final form of the interior yourself?
We approved all designs, including technical drawings and material samples, but the design always came from the architects.
At the beginning, we defined what we expected from the design and showed some interior elements that we would like to incorporate into the design, such as carpets or paintings.
I think that it was our collection of mainly Czech authors, including the works of Karel Malich, Karel Vysušil, Václav Špála or Otto Gutfreund, that helped the architect to navigate our taste.
The combination of black, white and walnut wood was also the architect&#39;s idea, as were the individual pieces of furniture, walls, floor, lighting, carpets, textiles, art, etc. We then checked together whether everything fits together using visualizations.
Were there any complications during the implementation, because of which you had to give up the original ideas, or, on the contrary, proceed with new ones?
Perhaps only at the initial stage of the project, when we came to the site at the moment when it was first possible to climb to the height of our floor, and found that the views we had planned were actually shadowed by the surrounding buildings.
That&#39;s when we literally changed the layout overnight.
Granite was used on the kitchen counter and on the fireplace wall paneling.
The interior is dominated by wooden surfaces supplemented with leather, for example on the upholstery of Norma dining and bar chairs by Arper.
How would you characterize the interior?
Are you planning any changes or is there anything you would like to have done differently today?
I believe that it is a modern, airy interior that above all fulfills its purpose.
We are not planning any changes, most of the modifications after moving in took place in the area of shading and housing the terraces.
Perhaps the only criticism is the floor, where walnut wood is too delicate for a household with a dog.
Word of architects, Ing. arch. Lenka Langerová and MgA. Kamila Hornychová, author of the implementation.
The apartment is on the top floor of a new building, so it was possible to carry out a completely new layout solution and several other modifications as part of the construction.
For the interior, an important element is the placement of light pipes in the ceiling of the corridor and the main toilet.
This brought daylight into the darker areas of the apartment.
Also, the direct entrance from the master bathroom to the roof terrace to the swimming pool from USSPA is one of the construction modifications that was very beneficial for the function of the entire apartment.
There is also a pool and hot tub.
Compared to the French, you are not negative, says a Muslim woman living in Prague.
You are from France.
Where did you live before you moved to Prague?
My parents are originally from Algeria.
I was born in the south of France, not far from the Spanish border.
I moved quite a lot.
I lived in Toulouse, Lyon and Marseille.
I studied journalism in France, thanks to which I got to work in a magazine.
So why did you decide to move out of the country?
I was starting to feel like I was suffocating in France.
I just didn&#39;t want to live there anymore.
Mainly because of the atmosphere among the people.
It seemed to me that every French person is terribly negative.
People in France are generally negative, but lately it has gotten worse.
It&#39;s interesting that you mention negativism.
This is how some people evaluate the Czech nature.
Trust me, you are not negative compared to the French.
Some people might not feel that way when they come to France because they don&#39;t see it as much as tourists.
But it was too much for me.
For example, money is a big topic.
People feel that they have little money, while the minimum wage in France is fifteen hundred euros, which I think is enough.
Now there is also a problem with people&#39;s behavior towards Muslims.
This is completely incomprehensible to me.
For example, in the street where I lived, my non-Muslim neighbor started to look down on me just because I am a Muslim.
Like I&#39;m some kind of evil.
That&#39;s why I didn&#39;t feel good in France.
But my family stayed there.
So you decided to go to another country.
Why did you choose the Czech Republic?
I was looking for a job basically anywhere else and I came across a vacancy at Air France here in Prague.
I admit that I didn&#39;t know Prague at all from the beginning.
I knew something about the Czech Republic, my father even told me about what happened in Czechoslovakia, but I had no idea what to expect from Prague.
I&#39;ve been here for three years now and I can&#39;t imagine not living here.
Was it a big difference when you moved from France to Prague?
Mainly because of the completely different atmosphere.
Maybe it&#39;s because I don&#39;t speak Czech, so I can&#39;t catch any negative reactions or swearing, but I feel that people are more free here.
That I can do anything, dress however I want and no one will judge me.
In France, someone always looks at you unpleasantly, for example, if you have strange clothes and the like.
I started to feel really free in Prague.
In my opinion, the people of Prague don&#39;t care about such things.
where do you work now
After working at Air France, I worked for a travel website for a while.
Then a friend and I set up a website where people offer and look for shared housing.
For now, we only operate in Prague, but we would like to expand it to the whole of Central Europe.
Do you have any Czech friends in Prague?
I have two very close friends here who are half Czech, and two more Czech friends.
I must say that another specific feature of the Czechs is that they keep their distance more at first.
He doesn&#39;t let anyone get close to him right away.
That&#39;s quite a difference from where I grew up.
In the south, everyone hugs and kisses the cheek.
It&#39;s different here, but I understand that it&#39;s a cultural thing, so I try to adapt.
You mentioned that you don&#39;t speak Czech.
Is the language barrier a problem for you?
On the contrary, it&#39;s quite easy for me in Prague, because everyone here speaks English.
Even in convenience stores or grocery stores.
I would like to learn Czech, but I don&#39;t have much time.
And since everyone can communicate at least a little in English, I don&#39;t have such a need to learn the language quickly.
And every time I have a problem, there is someone to help me.
Have you encountered any negative reactions?
Maybe because you are Muslim?
Basically no.
Maybe it&#39;s also because I work in an international environment that is more tolerant.
One experience comes to mind.
My supervisor, a Czech woman, once told me about the French football team and said something to the effect of: After all, they are not French, but African.
That touched me quite a bit.
But it has never happened to me that someone would have a problem with the fact that I am a Muslim.
And this despite the fact that a colleague once alerted me to some anti-Muslim demonstrations.
He told me not to go to the center, that they would scold me there.
Anti-Muslim demonstrations are partly linked to terrorist attacks.
How does the current situation affect you?
Are you afraid that something similar to Paris, Nice or Brussels could happen in Prague?
I feel safe in Prague.
But the problem is that nowadays anything can happen anywhere.
Until recently, I couldn&#39;t even imagine that something like this would happen in France.
And it&#39;s not just Muslims.
Moreover, Islam does not recognize violence at all.
To me, people who kill are not Muslims.
The Koran says that man has no right to kill because he is not God.
How do you feel when terrorists protect themselves with your faith?
It is very difficult.
I feel shame and guilt, even though I shouldn&#39;t feel that way at all.
I try not to watch the news about violence too much, but every time I read something, I feel the need to apologize for something that isn&#39;t really my fault.
I&#39;m a completely different person, so why should I apologize for terrorists?
We met at Jiřího z Poděbrady square.
On Wednesday, Czech Muslims together with Christians demonstrated here against violence.
Did you register it?
I didn&#39;t know about that.
But I understand that those people feel the need to prove that they do not agree with violence.
I don&#39;t think they have to do something like that.
Why should they feel guilty for something they didn&#39;t cause?
Do you meet other Muslims in Prague?
For example, my co-workers are from Egypt and other Muslim countries.
They are a bit more religious than I am, so we sometimes have quite wild discussions about Islam, because we each see it a little differently.
I come from France, so I had a different education, for example they learned Islam at school.
We have different approaches, but we respect each other.
People sometimes associate Islam with the subordinate position of women.
How do you perceive it?
I do not consider myself subordinate in any way.
On the contrary.
I am a woman, I have power.
The fact that you don&#39;t wear any headgear is also related to this.
For example the hijab?
And it&#39;s mainly the way I was brought up.
My mom, for example, is a really principled Muslim.
She prays five times a day, but she simply does not wear a scarf.
She always taught me that faith is a purely personal thing.
It depends on everyone how they interpret it.
When a person reads the Quran, he should make up his own mind about those things.
So when I read a passage in the Qur&#39;an that says God told the Prophet to hide his wives from the eyes of others, I said to myself: I am not the Prophet&#39;s wife, so why should I hide?
On the other hand, I respect it, and when I travel to Iran or Saudi Arabia, for example, where headscarves are required, I will take it.
Are you planning to stay in Prague?
So far.
I have never felt so good anywhere else.
I thought about Poland for a while, but I feel great in Prague.
I can even imagine raising my own children here.
In my opinion, Prague is the ideal city for that.
