TV director Matěj Liška and the manager of the Prague music club Marek Greger are behind the idea of using already planned routes for transporting shipments.
With the idea, they breathed life into a trio of applications with different geographical reach.
We launched the Převeza domestic application in May.
At the moment, it has a thousand cities uploaded and we will expand the network.
We want to learn it in the Czech Republic first, before we focus more on abroad, says the forty-one-year-old manager in an interview for iDNES.cz.
How does the Převezu application work and who can benefit from it?
You download it and register for free.
Then you can enter the route and information on how big a package you can transport and how much you want for it.
Someone might ask for a ride that day.
When the route and delivery time are suitable, it is paired and both receive a mutual notification.
At that moment, a chat will open, where the pair will arrange a handover.
How many people do you think would have to register so that every package always finds its courier?
I don&#39;t know the ideal situation, I can&#39;t estimate how many registered and how many trips are needed so that the coverage is completely optimal and each offer is paired with the demand.
It already works on the main routes and is logically easier than, for example, on the road between villages.
The more people, the greater the potential for speed and accuracy.
People are also still building trust and realizing that no one will run away with the package.
Have you not had to deal with such a case yet?
How many users does the service have after two months of launch?
We currently have about 5 to 6 thousand people creating paths.
We consider this a success and believe that more will be packed.
Is there a risk that the sender will wait too long?
We hope to be a competitor to the big conglomerates just because we are able to deliver the item on the same day and for a fraction of the price.
With a large company, you will pay several thousand for delivery within two hours.
Here you will pay maybe a hundred or less, because this is a path that someone is already taking.
Should traditional carriers be concerned about the possible loss of customers in the future?
We hope so.
The market has huge potential, huge multinational carriers feed here, as well as retail chains, where everyone started buying and gradually found out that the quality does not correspond to what they pay for.
No one wants to find a note in their mailbox saying that they should pick up the package at the branch, after 7 p.m. that day at the earliest.
After all, by that time I needed the package for six hours and I waited at home because it was important.
We want a better, faster and functional service that won&#39;t annoy anyone and will send a signal to the competition to keep trying.
Marek Greger (41) and Matěj Liška (39).
