Bulgaria reported inflation for the first time in eight months
According to national statistics, the monthly inflation rate in Bulgaria reached 1% in July.
This is the highest reading in several years (since June 2012) and the first non-zero reading since October last year, when a positive inflation rate of 0.2% was published.
The annual average rate of inflation, measured by the CPI index, for the last 12 months (August 2015 - July 2016) compared to the previous 12 month period (August 2014 - July 2015) was -0.8%.
The Consumer Price Index in July 2016 compared to June 2016 was 101.0%, so monthly inflation was 1.0%.
The year-to-date inflation rate (July 2016 versus December 2015) was -0.2% and the annual inflation rate in July 2016 versus July 2015 was -0.2%.
Compared to the previous month, in July 2016 there was an increase in trips of the following groups of consumer goods: food and non-alcoholic beverages (1.7%), transport (1.8%), culture and recreation (6.3%), restaurants and hotels (1, 2%), other goods and services (0.3%).
Prices fell for clothing and footwear (2.2%), furniture, household equipment and general maintenance (0.5%), health (0.1%).
Prices for alcoholic beverages and tobacco products, housing, water, electricity, gas and other fuels, communication and education remained at the same level as the previous month.
