There was a dangerous parasite in smoked salmon from Alberta.
The chain apologized.
On the basis of a consumer complaint about health problems after consuming the food Wild smoked salmon - pieces 100 g, expiry date 22 November 2016, Prague hygienists carried out an inspection in the Albert stores on Wenceslas Square and Na Můstek.
The inspection found that the batch L23012562/T4 with an expiry date of 22/11/2016, which the customer had pointed out, was no longer available, therefore the product of the same batch with an expiry date of 11/12/2016 was withdrawn.
Laboratory examination confirmed the presence of Anisakis spp. Anisakis simplex.
It is a parasitic worm of the digestive tract of marine mammals.
The latter is dangerous for humans - larvae in the body cavity or muscle of fish are a strong allergen, and live larvae eaten by humans can penetrate through the stomach wall into the internal organs, said Šticha.
We sincerely apologize to customers for the problems with this branded product.
We have immediately withdrawn the said batch from sale and, as a precaution, we have also withdrawn all other batches of this item.
The mistake occurred on the part of the supplier with whom we are negotiating, and at the same time we had this product tested ourselves, spokeswoman for Alberta Barbora Vanko told Novinka.
If the customer has purchased this product, he can return it to any of the chain&#39;s stores and receive a refund.
Frost and sufficient heat treatment will destroy the larvae
The seller was the company Nekton - Vrňata.
Hygienists informed the Prague and Central Bohemian Veterinary Administration about the presence of a dangerous product.
According to the server bezpecnostpotravin.cz, people can get sick with anisakiosis after eating the parasite, which is manifested by severe abdominal pain, vomiting and nausea, or the disease can be asymptomatic, ČTK reported.
Symptoms appear one to two weeks after eating undercooked infected fish.
After three weeks from the onset of the disease, the larvae usually spontaneously leave the digestive tract.
Both adult worms and larvae are sensitive to high and low temperatures, therefore they are killed either when the fish meat is sufficiently heat-treated or when it is frozen.
Veterinarians also checked the salmon at the recipient of the imported goods in the Central Bohemia region.
Three of the five samples examined had the parasite in them.
According to the State Veterinary Administration (SVS), the shipment with 1,700 products arrived in the Czech Republic at the beginning of April.
To date, 919 packages have been dispatched, the vast majority to the Ahold chain.
Unsold stocks of the product are currently being withdrawn from stores, SVS spokesman Petr Pejchal told ČTK on Friday.
Veterinarians immediately banned the shipment of other products from the warehouse after finding positive samples.
