Snapchat&#39;s filters have drawn criticism in the past, with accusations that the app promotes blackfacing or that it promotes white skin tones as the ideal of beauty.
So when it offered users a filter this week that gave users slanted eyes, crooked teeth and puffy faces, some critics called it a racist caricature of Asians - &quot;yellowface.&quot;
And they wondered if these repeated contentious questions pointed to a larger problem in society - a problem with diversity.
The Verge and Motherboard wrote about it on Wednesday, and the news and outrage quickly spread, with Snapchat announcing the very next day that it was removing the feature.
The company offered an explanation: The filter was intended as a tribute to anime characters, not a caricature of Asians.
But to observers who witnessed racism, the filter reminded them of painful stereotypes in action.
Others bluntly rejected the comparison to animé.
Grace Sparapani, a Korean American art student whose tweet about the photos was widely shared, said in an email that the filter was &quot;harmful and embarrassing, to say the least.&quot;
She added that &quot;it&#39;s hard to argue against comparing blatant Asian caricature and filter effects.&quot;
It turns out that the filter is not only about yellowface, but that yellowface is taken to a contemptuous extreme.
Snapchat isn&#39;t the only company that has crossed these cultural boundaries.
From corporate boardrooms to Hollywood and the devices we all carry in our hands, American culture seems to have a never-ending struggle for diversity and inclusion.
And the sheer number of young people on Snapchat — who are more racially diverse than their older counterparts — may mean even more sensitivity is to be expected.
&quot;When one Snapchat filter creates an image that&#39;s offensive to some user,&quot; Katie Zhu, 25, said in an interview Thursday, &quot;it&#39;s very hard to go unnoticed today like it used to.&quot;
Katie Zhu, a product manager and designer who works for Medium, decided to delete her Snapchat account on Thursday and urged others to do the same.
In an article for Medium and in a phone interview, she said she believes the racially motivated issues reflect a lack of diversity in Snapchat&#39;s hiring process.
Katie Zhu criticized the company&#39;s overwhelmingly white, all-male leadership and ended the article with the hashtag: #DeleteSnapchat.
“It&#39;s either that they don&#39;t have diversity on staff and people of color at the time these things are being decided,” said Zhu, who is Chinese-American, “or people of color are working there but not in positions to they felt safe or comfortable to speak up.”
Other observers share her view — a complaint that Snapchat has left largely unanswered.
The company does not release figures regarding the diversity of its employees, saying it has the status of a private company.
On Thursday, Snapchat declined to discuss the racial background of its employees, but a spokesperson said the company recently hired a recruiter to focus on underrepresented populations and internal inclusion management.
Zhu adds, &quot;I wonder if they really need more users like that who can say it&#39;s wrong,&quot; adding that her account will remain suspended.
Army officers misrepresented intelligence on IS, says parliamentary committee
A parliamentary committee said in a report released Thursday that officers at United States Central Command altered intelligence reports to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic State group in Iraq and Syria than events on the ground provided.
According to a preliminary report by a task force assembled by the Republican chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, the House Intelligence Committee and the Subcommittee on Defense, there was &quot;widespread dissatisfaction&quot; among Central Intelligence Agency analysts who said their superiors were changing their assessment of America&#39;s efforts to defeat the Islamic State.
Central Command, known as CentCom, is the Army headquarters in Tampa, Florida that oversees US military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
A press statement on the report stated, &quot;Intelligence statements endorsed by senior Centcom officers typically offered a more positive picture of U.S. counterterrorism efforts than was borne out by facts on the ground, and were consistently more positive than analyzes obtained from other parts of the intelligence community.&quot;
&quot;What happened at Centcom is unacceptable -- our warfighters are harmed when senior policymakers are presented with flawed analysis,&quot; said Ken Calvert, a congressman and Republican from California.
Centcom&#39;s leadership failure extends to the top of the organization.
The 10-page report details the Central Staff&#39;s continuing problems in describing and analyzing US efforts to train Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
While no conclusive evidence was offered that senior Obama administration officials ordered the reports to be altered, the report said analysts felt pressured by Centcom leaders to present a more optimistic view of the threat posed by the Islamic State , or IS.
&quot;In the first half of 2015, many central staff press releases, statements and statements from Congress were significantly more positive than what actually happened,&quot; the report said.
For example, a Centcom official has publicly stated that a major military offensive to retake Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq&#39;s second largest city, remains under the control of the Islamic State.
&quot;This is abundantly clear after months of investigation,&quot; Rep. Mike Pompeo, R-Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the highest-ranking US Central Staff intelligence officials manipulated the staff&#39;s intelligence outputs to downplay the danger of IS in Iraq.
Republicans formed the task force after learning of analysts&#39; concerns that intelligence information on the Islamic State was being manipulated.
A report released on Thursday is subject to further investigation following a more detailed investigation.
Another investigation is underway at Centcom Intelligence, led by the Defense Department&#39;s inspector general.
Democratic members of the Intelligence Committee released their own findings Thursday, which echoed some of the Republican task force&#39;s conclusions.
&quot;Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created a very narrow process for compiling intelligence assessments of IS and Iraqi security forces,&quot; Rep. Adam B. Schiff, the committee&#39;s chairman and a Democrat, said in a statement.
In the words of Adam Schiff, the process &quot;led to a distortion of intelligence output,&quot; damaged morale among analysts, and &quot;failed to accommodate dissenting views.&quot;
However, Schiff and Democrats say they have found no evidence that the White House tried to pressure Centcom analysts to adjust their conclusions based on &quot;the blueprint or the political situation.&quot;
The preliminary results of the parliamentary investigation were published in the Daily Beast on Tuesday.
Last August, the New York Times reported on an ongoing investigation by the Pentagon&#39;s inspector general, which was launched after complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lt. Commander Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Defense Department would not comment on the parliamentary report because the inspector general&#39;s investigation was still ongoing.
But he said that &quot;experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and that the intelligence community and the Department of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue about these critical national security issues.&quot;
The investigation has implications beyond the question of whether the American-led bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria is succeeding (a claim now being made by a growing number of defense officials).
However, last year&#39;s allegations have raised questions about the extent to which President Obama can rely on the Central Command&#39;s honest assessment of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis hotspots.
Intelligence criticism of the Islamic State reflects conflicts for more than a decade, with Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker writing a research paper that said President George W. Bush&#39;s administration — despite the objections of many analysts — advocated a small force in Iraq and devoted only little time to think about what would follow the 2003 invasion.
Hooker also played a key role in the resistance against Islamic State intelligence.
Last year, authorities announced that Hooker&#39;s team concluded that, despite public claims to the contrary, airstrikes against Islamic State refineries have not significantly weakened the terrorist group&#39;s financial resources because the group has built temporary refineries and sells oil on the black market.
The Times reported in September that the findings had not been passed on outside of central headquarters.
Centcom Commander, Gen. Lloyd J. Austin III, then came under fire last year after many lawmakers found Senate testimony overly positive about the war.
Gen. Austin resigned in April and was replaced at Centcom by Gen. Joseph L. Votel.
