Zen trampolines in the middle of the Olympic frenzy
It doesn&#39;t matter where you are, it doesn&#39;t matter what time it is - it&#39;s the Olympics.
There is a persistent, indescribable and biased alternation of competitiveness and effort from the events in Rio de Janeiro.
It is as if the Olympic torch itself were a red-hot relay leg being passed from swimmer to gymnast to triathlete.
You can&#39;t turn on the TV, read the paper, or listen to your neighbor&#39;s conversation in line at the coffee shop without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the feud between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
And then there&#39;s Logan Dooley.
Dooley, the up-and-coming darling of dimpled women, is in his first Olympics and could also be among those whose names ring in prime-time households between commercials and sponsor spots if he were a swimmer, a gymnast or even a fencer.
But Dooley, 28, of Lake Forest, Calif., is fighting for Olympic gold in springboard diving.
The Olympic flame does not shine equally for all competitions.
Far from the center, a little in the shadows, there are sports that are not universally recognized: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
We will always have success in the classic swimming style - and it will probably reign for a long time.
But if I can name an extraordinary favorite, let me point to the understated charm of the trampoline.
Although trampoline jumping has been an Olympic sport since it was first introduced at the Sydney Games in 2000, after 16 years of intervention the sport remains largely unnoticed - many people I interviewed did not even know it was an Olympic sport.
It could be regional indifference.
The U.S. has never won a medal in springboard jumping, and until 2012, none of the athletes even made it to the finals.
Prizes in the men&#39;s category are usually shared between China and Russia and in the women&#39;s category between China and Canada.
This year, the gold medals from London will be won by Dong Dong from China and Rosie MacLennan from Canada.
Trampoline jumping, however, has another misfortune, partly because to the uninitiated it will seem more suited to clown university than the Olympics.
I have to admit that I am not an expert, but only an enthusiast watching from the ground.
It has comic potential - the comic vibes of endless bouncing - but also the gracefulness of gymnastics and diving, the two sports it combines.
The word &quot;trampoline&quot; is derived from the Spanish &quot;el trampolín&quot; which means &quot;spring board.&quot;
Aspiring champions jump onto a giant trampoline that launches them almost 10 meters high and perform multi-element routines (somersaults, twists and combinations) before finally landing on their feet again.
According to the official Olympic program, they are graded according to execution, difficulty and &quot;time in the air&quot;.
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The usual trajectory of the Olympic track is forward.
Gold medalists must go further, faster and higher, sometimes to the end, sometimes back and forth, up and down.
They are trying to catch up not only to the finish line or the starting wall, but also, as the TV news reports, to another imaginary line: the world or Olympic record.
This single-minded effort is classy, admirable, a little fanatical - and enough to bring viewers to tears.
But I think it&#39;s also kind of exhausting when you watch the Olympics.
Trampoline jumps bring relief in this regard.
The trajectory of the athlete on the trampoline is upward.
The point is not to move forward.
He or she bounces as if in a weightless state like an astronaut, flying up, then down, then up again effortlessly.
It cannot be done without competition and, of course, difficulty, but for the duration of the composition there is no fierce struggle to reach the goal, no measuring of distance, but only a perfect, graceful springing of time and gravity.
This is the closest the Olympics and Zen will ever come.
The women&#39;s qualifiers and finals take place on Friday afternoon at 1pm ET, with the men&#39;s competition on Saturday at the same time.
NBC will air the finals in an afternoon slot starting at 2 p.m. both days.
In the middle of the Olympic frenzy, they promise calm, pleasant moments that you will probably overlook due to the other fights.
And if the only way to get attention is by making male athletes the object of amorous gazes and objectification - as USA gymnasts recently suggested, according to the Wall Street Journal - then Logan Dooley is just waiting for his new fans to gasp.
A &quot;Protesting Generation&quot; in Ethiopia, a longtime US ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia have met with violent resistance from the government.
Witnesses say many protesters were shot during clashes with police.
Is there a threat of war in Ethiopia?
In the past decade, it has been one of the most stable nations in Africa, a solid Western alliance with a fast-growing economy.
But in recent months, the country has been gripped by anti-government unrest, which is spreading to more and more areas.
In the last week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding fundamental political changes.
According to human rights organizations, the government&#39;s response was merciless.
Witnesses say police shot and killed crowds of unarmed protesters.
In circulating video footage of the protests, believed to date from late last year or early this year, security forces are seen beating young people with sticks after they were forced to stand on their hands against a wall.
The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
&quot;It has always been difficult to hold this country together and it will be even more difficult to take a step forward,&quot; said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project for the International Crisis Group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous nation in Africa after Nigeria and its stability is supported by the West.
US military and intelligence agencies are working closely with the Ethiopians to eliminate the threat of a terrorist attack in the region, especially in Somalia, and few, if any, African countries receive such help from the West.
Ethiopia&#39;s economy has developed at an impressive pace.
Its infrastructure has been fundamentally improved - there is even a new suburban train running in the capital Addis Ababa.
And the city streets are typically quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia can hardly be described as a model of democracy - organizations fighting for human rights constantly talk about government repression - opposition in the country was suppressed, dissidents were effectively silenced.
Many were banished, imprisoned, put to death or driven far into the desert.
However, this may change.
&quot;When you stifle people and they have no choice but to protest, there is a breakthrough,&quot; said Seyoum Teshome, who lectures at a university in central Ethiopia.
All the youth are protesting.
A whole generation is protesting.
Grievances are numerous and range from land disputes to the ruling coalition&#39;s absolute grip on power.
After last year&#39;s widely criticized election, the ruling party and its allies won the last seat held by the opposition and now controls 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, pressure is increasing on the border with Eritrea. The conflict along this imprecisely marked, disputed border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less suppressed over the past years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to take advantage of the confusion and rearm.
There are several factors that explain why, after years of simmering under the surface, these bitter feelings have re-ignited.
The first is seemingly innocuous: smartphones.
Many Ethiopians have only been able to communicate via social media in the last few years, when cheaper smartphones became common and internet service delivery improved.
And even if the government blocks access to Facebook or Twitter, as is common especially during protests, many people can still communicate through Internet proxies that hide their location.
Several young Ethiopians spoke of how they gathered for protests.
Furthermore, there is greater solidarity between the Oromo and the Amhara, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
Oromos and Amharas are not natural allies.
For centuries the Amharas, mostly from the Christian highlands of Ethiopia, excelled in politics and trade, exploiting the Oromo, many of whom are Muslim and live in the lowlands.
But that is also changing.
&quot;We are on the way to a unified leadership,&quot; said Mulatu Gemechu, an Oromo leader.
The largest protests occurred in areas populated by Amhara and Oromo people.
Many Amharas and Oromos believe that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which make up about 6 percent of the population and control the military, intelligence services, business and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Zenawi, a former rebel leader, was Ethiopia&#39;s prime minister for 17 years until his death in 2012, when he succumbed to an undisclosed illness.
He was considered a tactical genius, someone who could see beyond the corner.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at detecting early signs of discontent, using emissaries to process opponents and win them over to his side.
&quot;The current regime lacks basic knowledge,&quot; said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia&#39;s new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, was plucked from relative obscurity to replace Zenawi.
Unlike Zenawi, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is from the south.
Analysts say he has no confidence in the Tigrean-dominated security services.
Many fear that more bloodshed will result.
The last time Ethiopia saw such unrest was in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts described as elections that the government botched and then stole.
A crackdown followed, during which many protesters were killed - though fewer than in previous months - and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts have praised Ethiopia&#39;s leaders for visionary infrastructure planning such as a new commuter train and measurable progress in the fight against poverty.
However, it is quite clear that this did not stop the gradual increase of disputes within the Ethiopian government.
And there is a dangerous ethnic formation.
Last month, protesters in the Amharic city of Gondar attacked Tigrean-owned business firms, and resentment against Tigreans on social media has become increasingly common.
Analysts say the protests embarrass the US and other Western allies.
The U.S. government uses Ethiopia as a base for drone overflights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently said the base had been closed.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, at the same time it does not want its ally to fall apart in an already volatile region.
&quot;That,&quot; said Abdi, &quot;is a very sharp edge of the blade.&quot;
