In the pre-crisis years, American cuisine, especially in rural areas, was an all-you-can-eat buffet.
Teams of women cooked for the farm workers and freshly baked pie was served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to starving Europeans during the First World War. &quot;A Square Meal&quot; traces the ways in which the nation coped with the fact that it was suddenly not a land of plenty.
