NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
According to NASA&#39;s new climate model projections, Venus was once habitable.
Scientists at NASA&#39;s Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to explore Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, whose surface is hot, devoid of water and saturated with CO2, may once have had conditions similar to those on Earth.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus&#39;s slow rotation rate could be explained by its dense atmosphere.
But according to the latest simulations, it appears that Venus once boasted a thin Earth-like atmosphere while rotating slowly.
The model also looked at the earlier topography of Venus.
The planet likely had areas drier than Earth, but once had enough water and geographic diversity to support life and provide protection against rapid evaporation.
Venus used to also use the Sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
&quot;In the GISS model simulation, Venus exposes its day side to the sun for nearly two months at a time during its slow rotation,&quot; explained GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a new report.
This is how the surface is heated and rain forms, which creates a thick layer of clouds that act like an umbrella and protect the surface from excessive solar heat.
The result is a climate with average temperatures that are actually slightly lower than Earth&#39;s present day.
The model constructed a story of Venus similar to the evolution previously hypothesized by planetary scientists.
Although Venus was probably habitable in the past -- over several billion years -- it was exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet radiation.
Its oceans evaporated and the water vapor was burned by ultraviolet light.
The hydrogen escaped, leaving only a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide, a deadly greenhouse gas -- that&#39;s Venus as we know it today.
The researchers published their results from a new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
Patrick Roy resigned as coach of the Colorado Avalanche
Patrick Roy resigned as coach and vice president of hockey operations for the Colorado Avalanche on Thursday, citing the inability to participate in the decision-making process on team matters.
Colorado executive vice president/general manager Joe Sakic confirmed the move and said the club will begin searching for a new coach immediately.
&quot;For the past three years, I have served as head coach and vice president of hockey operations for the Colorado Avalanche with energy, passion and determination,&quot; Roy, 50, said in a statement.
I thought long and hard over the summer about how I can improve the team, give it the depth it needs and take it to a higher level.
In order to achieve this, it is necessary that the visions of the coach and vice president of hockey operations align with the vision of the organization.
They must also be able to participate in decisions that impact the team&#39;s performance.
These conditions are currently not met.
Sakic, who welcomed Roy on May 23, 2013, thanked him for his contributions to the team.
&quot;Patrick informed me of his decision today,&quot; Sakic said.
We appreciate everything he has done for our organization and wish him the best of luck in the future.
Roy was nominated for the Jack Adams Award as the league&#39;s top coach during his first season with the Avalanche in 2013/2014.
He led the team to 112 points and first place in the Central Division. But Colorado faced Minnesota in the first round of the playoffs and has consistently missed the postseason over the past two years.
The Avalanche went 39-39-4 in 2015/2016 and fell five points short of the second wild card in the Western Conference.
Hall of Fame goaltender Roy won the Stanley Cup four times -- twice with the Montreal Canadiens and twice with the Avalanche.
