Kepler measures the rotation speed of stars in the Pleiades
The Kepler Space Telescope&#39;s latest mission to help astronomers is to obtain an almost complete list of the rotation rates of the stars in the Pleiades star cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why the stars in the cluster rotate at different rates, as well as how the rotation period relates to planet formation.
&quot;By comparing our results with other star clusters, we hope to learn more about the relationship between a star&#39;s mass, its age, and even its history in its solar system,&quot; Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech&#39;s Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, said in the new report.
The Pleiades star cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are now just reaching maturity and have formed over about 125 million years.
Now it spins the fastest.
At moments of maximum rotation rates, these teenage stars release enormous amounts of stellar wind.
Because these winds move along the stars&#39; magnetic fields, they have a slowing effect on them.
As a star ages, its rotation rate slows down.
Kepler measures each star&#39;s rotation rate by measuring the time between the appearance of recognizable spots on the stars -- similar to sunspots.
According to the latest data on rotation rates, larger stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebullová compares stars to dancers, bigger ones do pirouettes more slowly than smaller ones.
&quot;In the &#39;ballet&#39; of the Pleiades, we see that the slower-spinning stars are more massive, while the fastest-spinning ones tend to be very light stars,&quot; Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades star cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory for comparing star quality and rotation rates.
&quot;The Pleiades provide us with an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, in younger and older stars,&quot; said Rebull.
There is still much we want to learn about how, when and why stars slow down their rotation rate and &quot;hang up their dancing shoes&quot; so to speak.
Rebull and her colleagues detailed the latest analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiades in three studies to be published soon in the Astronomical Journal.
Is a qualifying agreement necessary?
If I did not sign up, then the qualification agreement would not be concluded and I could transfer to another hospital after a few months?
Is it even possible to work after completing your studies without enrolling in specialized education?
The issue for me is that in the field in which I would like to work, there is currently a vacancy only in a hospital somewhat further away, but in about six months a position could become available in another where I would then like to work.
So I have no idea how to solve the situation for about six months, the question continues.
It is answered by Mgr. Lenka Vlková.
No legal regulation stipulates the obligation to conclude a qualification agreement with the employer - hospital.
A qualification agreement is a legal institution governed by the Labor Code, and it can be concluded between an employee and an employer in order to ensure the return of the costs incurred in connection with increasing or deepening the employee&#39;s qualifications.
In the field of health care, there is long-term pressure not to conclude these agreements with regard to ensuring the work mobility of health workers, and not all hospitals currently require this agreement.
According to Act No. 95/2004 Coll., on the conditions for obtaining and recognizing professional competence and specialized competence to perform the medical profession of doctor, dentist and pharmacist, it is expressly stated that participation in specialized education is considered to deepen the qualification (not to increase it ).
This means that, according to the Labor Code, a qualification agreement can only be concluded if the costs reach at least CZK 75,000.
No legal regulation even stipulates the obligation to register for specialized education.
The law only stipulates the conditions of the application for inclusion in the field of specialized education.
However, according to the law, a doctor is entitled to practice the profession of a doctor already by completing the necessary university studies, albeit under the conditions set by law (under the professional supervision of a doctor with specialized qualifications in the relevant field).
The law foresees a situation where professional practice completed in another field of specialization can be included in the specialized education of a doctor, if its content and scope correspond to the relevant educational program.
In theory, it would thus be possible to count the time worked elsewhere, which would correspond to the interviewer&#39;s situation.
However, considering the fact that I do not know the specific circumstances of this case, it is recommended to consult with the relevant department of the Ministry of Health (Department of Science and Medical Professions), as the Ministry of Health provides by law an advisory and consulting service related to inclusion in specialized education and its course.
The consulting service is also provided free of charge by the Czech Medical Chamber, of which every doctor must be a member.
